info.name: MarkLogic API REST
info.description: The REST API used in the IMSS Data Governance project let you querying information from the `data-hub-FINAL` database in MarkLogic. Through this API, users can access detailed information and perform parameterized searches via endpoints, facilitating efficient data extraction and management.

item.name: Menu Resources

request.description:
### **Description**

Returns a list of entity facets with the frequency of properties that have the facet attribute, segmented by categories: Technology, People, Processes and Domains.

### Structure

- Main menu is category
    
- Submenu is entities
    
- Sub-submenu is facets

response.name: Successful Response

item.description: The `/v1/_describeModel.sjs` endpoint let you to read all the entities with their respective facets to create a menu by category, entities and facets.

item.name: Facets Entities

request.description:
### **Description**

Provides a list of entity facets with the frequency of properties that have the facet attribute.

response.name: Successful Response

item.description: The `/api/describeModel.sjs` endpoint let you to read all the entities with their respective facets.

item.name: Parameterized Search

query.description: The name of the query options previously created via a PUT or POST request to /v1/config/query service
The name of the query options previously created via a PUT or POST request to /v1/config/query
The index of the first result to return. Results are numbered beginning with 1. Default: 1.
Filter search results to include only matches in the named collection. If you specify this parameter multiple times, the collections are OR related.

A string query expressed in the Search API grammar. You can use search operators such as AND, OR, or NEAR to combine terms in the search field. This is useful when you want to search for multiple keywords in your documents or entities.

The category of data to fetch about the matching documents. Category can be specified multiple times to retrieve any combination of content and metadata. Valid categories: content (default), metadata, metadata-values, collections, permissions, properties, and quality. Use metadata to request all categories except content. You can only use this parameter when making a multi-document read request.
The view of the search results to return in the response. Accepted values: facets, results, metadata, all. Default: all for a normal search, none for a multi-document read.
Specify the content type of returned metadata and the search results (if requested) in the response; format has no effect on returned document content. Accepted values: json or xml. Default: xml.
The transaction identifier of the multi-statement transaction in which to service this request. Use the /transactions service to create and manage multi-statement transactions.
Filter search results to include only matches from documents in the specified database directory.

Names a search result transformation previously installed via the /transforms service. The transformation is applied to the <search:response/> after applying user-defined transforms defined in the query options using <transform-results>.
A transform parameter name and value. For example, trans:myparam=1. Transform parameters are passed to the transform named in the transform parameter.
A timestamp returned in the ML-Effective-Timestamp header of a previous request. Use this parameter to iteratively fetch search results based on the contents of the database at a fixed point-in-time.

The name of forest(s) to which results should be limited. The forest(s) must exist in the database for this request. If you wish to retrieve results from multiple specific forests, specify this parameter once per forest.
A structured query or cts:query as a string. That is, a serialized representation of a search:query element or a cts:query.
Perform this operation on the named content database instead of the default content database associated with the REST API instance.

item.name: Users

request.description:
### **Description**

This endpoint retrieves the properties of a specific user in a specified format. The response returned is in JSON format and includes the user's name, description, roles in MarkLogc and rol for app.

Note: the user must exist in MarkLogic and it can be searched by name or id

item.description: The `/manage/v2/users/[id-or-name]/properties` endpoint lets you query information about the user that exists in MarkLogic
